ategory:Circumnavigators of the globe]]\n[[Category:Deaths by stabbing in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:English cartographers]]\n[[Category:English explorers of North America]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:English sailors]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Explorers of British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Explorers of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Oregon]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Hydrographers]]\n[[Category:James Cook| ]]\n[[Category:Maritime writers]]\n[[Category:Murdered explorers]]\n[[Category:People from Middlesbrough]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Persons of National Historic Significance (Canada)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Copley Medal]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers]]\n[[Category:Q150 Icons]]\n[[Category:Sea captains]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Antarctica]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript| Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Cook"}
{"title_page": "Murphy Troy", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name             = Murphy Troy\n| image            = Murphy Troy.JPG\n| image_size       = <!-- Leave this blank for the default size -->\n| caption          = \n| fullname         = Murphy Edward Troy\n| nationality      = [[United States|American]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1989|5|31|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[St. Louis]], Missouri, U.S.\n| height           = {{convert|2.02|m|ftin|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| weight           = {{convert|99|kg|lb|0|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| spike            = {{convert|360|cm|in|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| block            = {{convert|350|cm|in|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| college          = [[University of Southern California]]\n| position         = Opposite\n| currentclub      = \n| currentnumber    = 11\n| years            = 2008\u20132011<br>2011\u20132013<br>2013\u20132014<br>2014\u20132016\n| teams            = [[USC Trojans men's volleyball|USC Trojans]]<br>[[Top Volley Latina|Andreoli Latina]]<br>[[Saint-Nazaire VBA]]<br>[[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]]\n| nationalyears    = 2011\u20132016\n| nationalteam     = {{vb|USA}}\n| medaltemplates-title = Medal record\n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalCompetition|[[Volleyball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Volleyball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|2015 Japan]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIVB World League|World League]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|2014 Florence]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|2015 Rio de Janeiro]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[NORCECA Men's Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|2013 Canada]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan American Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|2012 Santo Domingo]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2011 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|2011 Gatineau]]|}}\n| updated          = 1 June 2017\n}}\n\n'''Murphy Edward Troy''' (born May 31, 1989) is a former American [[volleyball]] player, a member of the [[United States men's national volleyball team]], [[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Champion 2013]], gold medalist of [[2012 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan-American Cup 2012]] and [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|World League 2014]].\n\n==Personal life==\nMurphy Troy married his long-time girlfriend Blair Tarnutzer on October 29, 2016 in [[La Quinta, California]].\n\nTroy enjoys visiting his sister Sarah \"Sadie\" Troy in Virginia, where she has worked as a Historical Interpreter at Thomas Jefferson's Monticello since 2014.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Clubs===\nIn 2014 Troy moved from [[France]] to Polish club [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]].<ref>[http://eurosport.onet.pl/siatkowka/plus-liga/plusliga-murphy-troy-siatkarzem-lotosu-trefla-gdansk/1r472 ''PlusLiga: Murphy Troy siatkarzem Lotosu Trefla Gda\u0144sk ''] \u2013 eurosport.onet.pl \u2013 July 9, 2014</ref> On April 19, 2015 he achieved [[2014\u201315 Polish Cup of men's volleyball|Polish Cup]], which is first trophy of [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]] in history of club.<ref>[http://www.sportowefakty.pl/siatkowka/515726/pp-historyczny-triumf-w-gdansku-relacja-z-meczu-lotos-trefl-gdansk-asseco-resovi ''PP: Historyczny triumf w Gda\u0144sku! - relacja z meczu Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk \u2013 Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w''] \u2013 sportowefakty.pl \u2013 April 19, 2015</ref> He was awarded a title of ''Best Server'' of tournament.<ref>[http://www.sportowefakty.pl/siatkowka/515587/pp-mezczyzn-mateusz-mika-z-nagroda-mvp-nagrody-indywidualne ''PP m\u0119\u017cczyzn: Mateusz Mika z nagrod\u0105 MVP \u2013 nagrody indywidualne''] \u2013 sportowefakty.pl \u2013 April 19, 2015</ref> Then he won with Polish club silver medal of [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]].<ref>[http://sport.trojmiasto.pl/Zloto-dla-Asseco-Resovii-srebro-dla-Gdanska-Lotos-Trefl-Gdansk-n89979.html ''Lotos Trefl wicemistrzem Polski siatkarzy \u2013 Z\u0142oto dla Asseco Resovii, srebro dla Gda\u0144ska''] \u2013 sport.trojmiasto.pl \u2013 April 28, 2015</ref> In May 2015 signed new one-year contract with [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]].<ref>[http://www.plusliga.pl/news/id/11203 ''Murphy Troy zostaje w Lotosie Treflu''] \u2013 plusliga.pl \u2013 May 6, 2015</ref> Troy left Gda\u0144sk in 2016. He announced his retirement on June 1, 2017.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n===National team===\nIn 2014 [[United States men's national volleyball team|American national team]], including Troy, won gold medal of the [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|World League]].\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n\n===Clubs===\n\n====National championships====\n* '''2014/2015''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 Polish Cup of men's volleyball|Polish Cup]], with [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]]\n* '''2014/2015''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]]\n* '''2015/2016''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Polish SuperCup 2015, with [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]]\n\n===National team===\n* '''2011''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2011 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan-American Cup]]\n* '''2012''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2012 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan-American Cup]]\n* '''2013''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]]\n* '''2014''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n* '''2015''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n* '''2015''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|FIVB World Cup]]\n* '''2016''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Volleyball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Olympic Games]]\n\n===Individual===\n* '''2015''' [[2014\u201315 Polish Cup of men's volleyball|Polish Cup]] \u2013 Best Server\n* '''2014/2015'''  [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Plus Liga]] \u2013 Top Scorer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n*{{USOPC profile|TR/Murphy-Troy}}\n*[http://www.plusliga.pl/players/id/26807/Troy-Murphy/ PlusLiga player profile]\n\n{{United States men volleyball team 2015 FIVB World Cup}}\n{{United States men's volleyball squad 2016 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Troy, Murphy}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:American men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Poland]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Poland]]\n[[Category:Trefl Gda\u0144sk players]]\n[[Category:Olympic volleyball players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for the United States in volleyball]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Russia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name             = Murphy Troy\n| image            = Murphy Troy.JPG\n| image_size       = <!-- Leave this blank for the default size -->\n| caption          = \n| fullname         = Murphy Edward Troy\n| nationality      = [[United States|American]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1989|5|31|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[St. Louis]], Missouri, U.S.\n| height           = {{convert|2.02|m|ftin|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| weight           = {{convert|99|kg|lb|0|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| spike            = {{convert|360|cm|in|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| block            = {{convert|350|cm|in|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| college          = [[University of Southern California]]\n| position         = Opposite\n| currentclub      = \n| currentnumber    = 11\n| years            = 2008\u20132011<br>2011\u20132013<br>2013\u20132014<br>2014\u20132016\n| teams            = [[USC Trojans men's volleyball|USC Trojans]]<br>[[Top Volley Latina|Andreoli Latina]]<br>[[Saint-Nazaire VBA]]<br>[[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]]\n| nationalyears    = 2011\u20132016\n| nationalteam     = {{vb|USA}}\n| medaltemplates-title = Medal record\n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalCompetition|[[Volleyball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Volleyball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|2015 Japan]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIVB World League|World League]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|2014 Florence]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|2015 Rio de Janeiro]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[NORCECA Men's Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|2013 Canada]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan American Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|2012 Santo Domingo]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2011 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|2011 Gatineau]]|}}\n| updated          = 1 June 2017\n}}\n\n'''Murphy Edward Troy''' (born May 31, 1989) is a former American [[volleyball]] player, a member of the [[United States men's national volleyball team]], [[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Champion 2013]], gold medalist of [[2012 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan-American Cup 2012]] and [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|World League 2014]].\n\n==Personal life==\nMurphy Troy married his long-time girlfriend Blair Tarnutzer on October 29, 2016 in [[La Quinta, California]].\n\nTroy enjoys visiting his sister Sarah \"Sadie\" Troy in Virginia, where she has worked as a Historical Interpreter at Thomas Jefferson's Monticello since 2014.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Clubs===\nIn 2014 Troy moved from [[France]] to Polish club [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]].<ref>[http://eurosport.onet.pl/siatkowka/plus-liga/plusliga-murphy-troy-siatkarzem-lotosu-trefla-gdansk/1r472 ''PlusLiga: Murphy Troy siatkarzem Lotosu Trefla Gda\u0144sk ''] \u2013 eurosport.onet.pl \u2013 July 9, 2014</ref> On April 19, 2015 he achieved [[2014\u201315 Polish Cup of men's volleyball|Polish Cup]], which is first trophy of [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]] in history of club.<ref>[http://www.sportowefakty.pl/siatkowka/515726/pp-historyczny-triumf-w-gdansku-relacja-z-meczu-lotos-trefl-gdansk-asseco-resovi ''PP: Historyczny triumf w Gda\u0144sku! - relacja z meczu Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk \u2013 Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w''] \u2013 sportowefakty.pl \u2013 April 19, 2015</ref> He was awarded a title of ''Best Server'' of tournament.<ref>[http://www.sportowefakty.pl/siatkowka/515587/pp-mezczyzn-mateusz-mika-z-nagroda-mvp-nagrody-indywidualne ''PP m\u0119\u017cczyzn: Mateusz Mika z nagrod\u0105 MVP \u2013 nagrody indywidualne''] \u2013 sportowefakty.pl \u2013 April 19, 2015</ref> Then he won with Polish club silver medal of [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]].<ref>[http://sport.trojmiasto.pl/Zloto-dla-Asseco-Resovii-srebro-dla-Gdanska-Lotos-Trefl-Gdansk-n89979.html ''Lotos Trefl wicemistrzem Polski siatkarzy \u2013 Z\u0142oto dla Asseco Resovii, srebro dla Gda\u0144ska''] \u2013 sport.trojmiasto.pl \u2013 April 28, 2015</ref> In May 2015 signed new one-year contract with [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]].<ref>[http://www.plusliga.pl/news/id/11203 ''Murphy Troy zostaje w Lotosie Treflu''] \u2013 plusliga.pl \u2013 May 6, 2015</ref> Troy left Gda\u0144sk in 2016. He announced his retirement on June 1, 2017.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n===National team===\nIn 2014 [[United States men's national volleyball team|American national team]], including Troy, won gold medal of the [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|World League]].\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n\n===Clubs===\n\n====National championships====\n* '''2014/2015''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 Polish Cup of men's volleyball|Polish Cup]], with [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]]\n* '''2014/2015''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]]\n* '''2015/2016''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Polish SuperCup 2015, with [[Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk]]\n\n===National team===\n* '''2011''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2011 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan-American Cup]]\n* '''2012''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2012 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan-American Cup]]\n* '''2013''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]]\n* '''2014''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n* '''2015''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n* '''2015''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|FIVB World Cup]]\n* '''2016''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Volleyball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Olympic Games]]\n\n===Individual===\n* '''2015''' [[2014\u201315 Polish Cup of men's volleyball|Polish Cup]] \u2013 Best Server\n* '''2014/2015'''  [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Plus Liga]] \u2013 Top Scorer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n*[http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/TR/Murphy-Troy.aspx Team USA player profile]\n*[http://www.plusliga.pl/players/id/26807/Troy-Murphy/ PlusLiga player profile]\n\n{{United States men volleyball team 2015 FIVB World Cup}}\n{{United States men's volleyball squad 2016 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Troy, Murphy}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:American men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Poland]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Poland]]\n[[Category:Trefl Gda\u0144sk players]]\n[[Category:Olympic volleyball players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for the United States in volleyball]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Russia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "use template for USOPC link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murphy_Troy"}
{"title_page": "It's Great to Be Young (1956 film)", "text_new": "{{for|the 1946 film|It's Great to Be Young (1946 film)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = It's Great to Be Young\n| image          = \"It's_Great_to_Be_Young\"_(1956_film).jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Cyril Frankel]]\n| producer       =  [[Victor Skutezky]]\n| writer         = [[Ted Willis]] (story and screenplay)\n| starring       = [[John Mills]]<br>[[Cecil Parker]]\n| music          = [[Louis Levy]] (musical director)\n| cinematography = [[Gilbert Taylor]]\n| editing        = [[Max Benedict]]\n| studio         = Marble Arch Productions\n| distributor    = Associated British-Path\u00e9 (UK)\n| released       = {{Film date|1956}}\n| runtime        = 94 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| gross          = \u00a3282,838<ref>Vincent Porter, 'The Robert Clark Account', ''Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television'', Vol 20 No 4, 2000 p510</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''It's Great to Be Young''''' is a 1956 [[musical film|musical]] [[Technicolor]] [[comedy film]] about a school music teacher, starring [[Cecil Parker]] and [[John Mills]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b6ad62856|title=It's Great to Be Young! (1956) - BFI|work=BFI}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nMr Dingle ([[John Mills]]) seeks to interest his pupils in music in order to enjoy life, while the new headmaster, Mr Frome ([[Cecil Parker]]) believes Dingle is ruining the children's traditional education. \n\nMr Dingle's pupils come up with a way to raise money by playing to crowds in the street and persuade Mr Dingle to help them. When this fails they decide to jazz it up and bring in some younger kids to help which is a success so, with the help of one of the pupil's parents, they are able to buy new musical instruments. \n\nHowever, when Mr Dingle ends up on the front page of the local newspaper, the headmaster locks the instruments up. The pupils manage to get them out of the locked cupboards, rehearse and put them back without anyone noticing. \n\nMr Dingle takes a job playing the piano in his local pub but he is spotted by one of the teachers who reports him to Mr Frome who sacks him for it. The children protest about Dingle being sacked by leading a strike and a sit in. \n\nEventually, order is restored as Mr Frome relents and allows Mr Dingle to return.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[John Mills]] as Mr. Dingle\n* [[Cecil Parker]] as Frome\n* [[John Salew]] as Routledge\n* Elizabeth Kentish as Mrs. Castle\n* [[Mona Washbourne]] as Miss Morrow\n* [[Mary Merrall]] as Miss Wyvern\n* [[Derek Blomfield]] as Paterson\n* [[Jeremy Spenser]] as Nicky\n* [[Dorothy Bromiley]] as Paulette\n* Brian Smith as Ginger\n* Wilfred Downing as Browning\n* Robert Dickens as Morris\n* Dawson France as Crowther\n* [[Carole Shelley]] as Peggy\n* [[Richard O'Sullivan]] as Lawson\n* [[Norman Pierce]] as Publican\n* [[Eleanor Summerfield]] as Barmaid\n* [[Bryan Forbes]] as Mr. Parkes, Organ Salesman\n* [[Marjorie Rhodes]] as Landlady\n* [[Eddie Byrne]] as Morris\n* [[Russell Waters]] as Mr. Scott, School Inspector\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe song \"You are My First Love\" is sung over the opening scenes of the film by [[Ruby Murray]]. Released on record, it reached number 16 in the UK charts.\n \n==Reception==\nThe film was one of the ten most popular films at the British box office in 1956.<ref>BRITISH. FILMS MADE MOST MONEY: BOX-OFFICE SURVEY\nThe Manchester Guardian (1901-1959) [Manchester (UK)] 28 Dec 1956: 3</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/Screen_Volume_32_Issue_3/page/n17|magazine=Screen|page=259|volume=32|issue=3|title=The popular cash and culture in the postwar British cinema industry|first=Janet|last=Thumim}}</ref>\n\n[[BFI Screenonline]] writes, \"''It's Great To Be Young!'' has a fair claim to be not only one of Britain's first teenage musicals but also one of the most commercially successful of any musical made in Britain during the 1950s - it proved so popular that it allegedly caused riots in [[Singapore]]. Its virtues are those of many [[Associated British Picture Corporation|ABPC productions]] of its era, from the vibrant [[Eastmancolor]] cinematography to the immaculately-selected cast and even if some of the sixth-formers are aged in their twenties, they do sound convincing as teenagers.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/1352177/index.html|title=BFI Screenonline: It's Great to Be Young! (1956)|work=screenonline.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://movies.aol.com/movie/its-great-to-be-young/1063377/synopsis Synopsis from Movies at AOL]\n* {{IMDb title|0049372|It's Great to Be Young}}\n*[http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/1352177/ ''It's Great to Be Young!'' at BFI Screenonline]\n\n[[Category:1956 films]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Elstree Studios]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:1950s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:British high school films]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the 1946 film|It's Great to Be Young (1946 film)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = It's Great to Be Young\n| image          = \"It's_Great_to_Be_Young\"_(1956_film).jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Cyril Frankel]]\n| producer       =  Victor Skutezky\n| writer         = [[Ted Willis]] (story and screenplay)\n| starring       = [[John Mills]]<br>[[Cecil Parker]]\n| music          = [[Louis Levy]] (musical director)\n| cinematography = [[Gilbert Taylor]]\n| editing        = [[Max Benedict]]\n| studio         = Marble Arch Productions\n| distributor    = Associated British-Path\u00e9 (UK)\n| released       = {{Film date|1956}}\n| runtime        = 94 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| gross          = \u00a3282,838<ref>Vincent Porter, 'The Robert Clark Account', ''Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television'', Vol 20 No 4, 2000 p510</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''It's Great to Be Young''''' is a 1956 [[musical film|musical]] [[Technicolor]] [[comedy film]] about a school music teacher, starring [[Cecil Parker]] and [[John Mills]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b6ad62856|title=It's Great to Be Young! (1956) - BFI|work=BFI}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nMr Dingle ([[John Mills]]) seeks to interest his pupils in music in order to enjoy life, while the new headmaster, Mr Frome ([[Cecil Parker]]) believes Dingle is ruining the children's traditional education. \n\nMr Dingle's pupils come up with a way to raise money by playing to crowds in the street and persuade Mr Dingle to help them. When this fails they decide to jazz it up and bring in some younger kids to help which is a success so, with the help of one of the pupil's parents, they are able to buy new musical instruments. \n\nHowever, when Mr Dingle ends up on the front page of the local newspaper, the headmaster locks the instruments up. The pupils manage to get them out of the locked cupboards, rehearse and put them back without anyone noticing. \n\nMr Dingle takes a job playing the piano in his local pub but he is spotted by one of the teachers who reports him to Mr Frome who sacks him for it. The children protest about Dingle being sacked by leading a strike and a sit in. \n\nEventually, order is restored as Mr Frome relents and allows Mr Dingle to return.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[John Mills]] as Mr. Dingle\n* [[Cecil Parker]] as Frome\n* [[John Salew]] as Routledge\n* Elizabeth Kentish as Mrs. Castle\n* [[Mona Washbourne]] as Miss Morrow\n* [[Mary Merrall]] as Miss Wyvern\n* [[Derek Blomfield]] as Paterson\n* [[Jeremy Spenser]] as Nicky\n* [[Dorothy Bromiley]] as Paulette\n* Brian Smith as Ginger\n* Wilfred Downing as Browning\n* Robert Dickens as Morris\n* Dawson France as Crowther\n* [[Carole Shelley]] as Peggy\n* [[Richard O'Sullivan]] as Lawson\n* [[Norman Pierce]] as Publican\n* [[Eleanor Summerfield]] as Barmaid\n* [[Bryan Forbes]] as Mr. Parkes, Organ Salesman\n* [[Marjorie Rhodes]] as Landlady\n* [[Eddie Byrne]] as Morris\n* [[Russell Waters]] as Mr. Scott, School Inspector\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe song \"You are My First Love\" is sung over the opening scenes of the film by [[Ruby Murray]]. Released on record, it reached number 16 in the UK charts.\n \n==Reception==\nThe film was one of the ten most popular films at the British box office in 1956.<ref>BRITISH. FILMS MADE MOST MONEY: BOX-OFFICE SURVEY\nThe Manchester Guardian (1901-1959) [Manchester (UK)] 28 Dec 1956: 3</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/Screen_Volume_32_Issue_3/page/n17|magazine=Screen|page=259|volume=32|issue=3|title=The popular cash and culture in the postwar British cinema industry|first=Janet|last=Thumim}}</ref>\n\n[[BFI Screenonline]] writes, \"''It's Great To Be Young!'' has a fair claim to be not only one of Britain's first teenage musicals but also one of the most commercially successful of any musical made in Britain during the 1950s - it proved so popular that it allegedly caused riots in [[Singapore]]. Its virtues are those of many [[Associated British Picture Corporation|ABPC productions]] of its era, from the vibrant [[Eastmancolor]] cinematography to the immaculately-selected cast and even if some of the sixth-formers are aged in their twenties, they do sound convincing as teenagers.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/1352177/index.html|title=BFI Screenonline: It's Great to Be Young! (1956)|work=screenonline.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://movies.aol.com/movie/its-great-to-be-young/1063377/synopsis Synopsis from Movies at AOL]\n* {{IMDb title|0049372|It's Great to Be Young}}\n*[http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/1352177/ ''It's Great to Be Young!'' at BFI Screenonline]\n\n[[Category:1956 films]]\n[[Category:Films shot at 